John Edward: Language Skills are Essential for the Citizens of the World
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a record of school excellence. This trend continued in 2018 with new excellent exam results reinforced by collective and individual success in sports, art, music and other community activities.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) strive to offer the best level of service to students and their parents.
Independent schools work to prepare their students for higher education, the career they have chosen, and their place as citizens of the world.
As an education sector capable of designing and implementing a tailor-made curriculum, we find that contemporary languages remain popular and desirable subjects in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, you speak to his head.
If you speak to him in his language, you speak to his heart.”
This reminds us that we cannot rely on English to build relationships and establish trust with residents of other countries.
If you look at the excellent results of the exams this year, you will find that the languages are at the top of the ranking, with the highest success rates within independent schools.
In total, 68% of students who studied foreign languages received the highest score, A.
The data, collected from the 74 SCIS member schools, shows that 72% of students have the highest score, A, in Mandarin, as well as 72% of students who have studied German, 69% of students who have studied French and 63% of students who have studied French.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as absolutely essential skills for children and young people in the future.
Now, languages as subjects are organized as well as science, technology, engineering and mathematics in the programs of independent schools and other schools.
A 2014 survey by the UK Employment and Skills Commission found that among the difficulties employers face in recruiting candidates, 17% are linked to insufficient language skills.
Language skills are therefore increasingly vital in preparing young people for their future careers.
With more jobs requiring languages, these skills are essential in our globalized world.
No matter his or her career choice, a person who speaks a second language will benefit from a real advantage in the future thanks to this lasting skill.
Being able to communicate directly with foreigners will automatically place the multilingual person in front of its competitors.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of 4,000 adults living in the UK, 75% of them did not speak a foreign language enough to have a conversation. French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage (15%).
This is why investing in language learning is important for children today.
By speaking several languages, including those in emerging economies, children will have a better chance of finding a rewarding job.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Several of them will focus on classical contemporary languages, while others will teach languages considered important to the UK in the 2020 outlook, including Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s preferences, several languages will be accessible in independent schools, with specialist staff in the field.
Scottish independent schools want to provide a learning environment that will prepare children and give them the skills needed to succeed, no matter what the future holds for them.
It is clear that today, in a global business environment, languages remain of crucial importance for the future of the country, which must be reflected in education.
Modern languages must be considered as “international communication skills”.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, this diversity and this excellence to Scottish youth.
We have to do it right.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
