The inventor of the World Wide Web plans to launch a New Internet to challenge Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, is launching a brand new company that is looking to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest technology legend project, Inrupt, is a company that takes advantage of Berners-Lee’s free platform Solid.
Solid allows users to choose where their data is stored as well as those authorized to access such or such information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee jokingly said Inrupt was aiming to “dominated the world.”
“We have to do it now,” he said about the launch.
“It’s a historic moment.”
The app uses Solid technology to enable people to create their own “online personal data store” or DPL.
This can contain contact lists, task lists, a calendar, a music library as well as other personal and professional tools.
It’s as if Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify were all available simultaneously on one browser.
The peculiarity of the online personal data store is that it is entirely up to the user to decide who can access what type of information.
The company calls this “personal responsibility through data”.
According to the company’s CEO, John Bruce, the idea of Inrupt is that the company brings the right resources, processes and skills to make Solid accessible to everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, a few contract developers working on the project, and a community of volunteer coders.
As of this week, tech developers around the world will be able to create their own decentralized applications using the tools available on Inrupt’s website.
Berners-Lee said his team and him are not yet in talks with Facebook and Google to find out whether or not to make a complete change where all their business models are completely blurred in an instant.
“We don’t ask them for permission.”
In an article published Saturday on Medium, Berners-Lee writes that the “mission [of Inrupt] is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem in order to protect the integrity and quality of the new web built on Solid.”
In 1994, at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet by creating the World Wide Web Consortium.
