Nickel mining is also an important activity in the province, but it is mainly located in Morowali, on the opposite coast of Sulawesi.
Palu and Donggala have been hit by tsunamis several times over the past century, according to the Indonesian Disaster Reduction Agency.
In 1938, a tsunami killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of homes in Donggala.
A tsunami also struck western Donggala in 1996, killing nine people.
Indonesia is located on the Pacific seismic fire circle and is regularly shaken by earthquakes.
Here are some of the major earthquakes and tsunamis in recent years:
2004: A major earthquake on the west coast of the Indonesian province of Aceh on December 26 triggered a tsunami in 14 countries, killing 226,000 off the coast of the Indian Ocean, more than half of them in Aceh.
2005: Several violent earthquakes struck the west coast of Sumatra from late March to early April.
Hundreds of people have died on the island of Nias, off Sumatra.
2006: An earthquake of magnitude 6.8 hits southern Java, Indonesia's most populous island, triggering a tsunami that hit the south coast and killed nearly 700 people.
2009: A 7.6-magnitude earthquake struck the city of Padang, the capital of West Sumatra province.
More than 1,100 people were killed.
2010: An earthquake of magnitude 7.5 devastated one of the Mentawai Islands off Sumatra, triggering a tsunami of more than 10 meters that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A surface earthquake shook the Pidie Jaya Regency in Aceh, causing destruction and panic, reminding residents of the devastation caused by the 2004 deadly earthquake and tsunami.
