Europe wins the Ryder Cup in Paris
The European team won the 2018 Ryder Cup by beating the United States team with a final score of 16.5 to 10.5 at the Golf National near Paris, France.
The United States have now lost six consecutive times on European soil and have not won a Ryder Cup in Europe since 1993.
Europe regained the title when the team of Danish captain Thomas Bjorn crossed the 14.5-point bar needed to beat the United States.
American star Phil Mickelson, who was in difficulty during most of the tournament, pushed his start in the water at the 16th hole in par-3, giving his duel to Francesco Molinari.
Italian golfer Molinari excelled in all his rounds, becoming one of the four players to have ever reached 5-0-0 since the current format of the tournament, whose first edition dates back to 1979.
The American Jordan Spieth was scored 5-4 by Denmark's lowest-ranked player, Thorbjorn Olesen.
The best golfer in the world, Dustin Johnson, leaned 2 and 1 against Englishman Ian Poulter, who may have played his last Ryder Cup.
