Red tide info point: Decreasing concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report of the Florida Fisheries and Wildlife Commission indicates a general decrease in red tide concentrations in certain areas of the Tampa Bay region.
According to the CPF, more irregular flowering conditions are reported in the areas of the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier - which makes fears of declining concentrations.
The red tide covers about 209 km (130 miles) of coastlines, from the north of Pinellas to the south of the counties of Lee.
There are islands about 16 km (10 miles) off Hillsborough County, but in fewer sites than last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Moderate concentrations in or off Pinellas County have been reported last week, low to high concentrations in Hillsborough County, higher concentrations in Manatee County, higher concentrations at the bottom of Sarasota County or offshore, average concentrations in the last county, and low concentrations in Charlotte County, and low concentrations in the bottom of the county.
Cases of respiratory irritation persist in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
No respiratory irritation has been reported in northwestern Florida over the past week.
